00:18:16,890 --> 00:18:18,870
But the average it goes away after about a month.
但平均来说一个月后会消退

328
00:18:19,220 --> 00:18:20,530
The spike to well-being.
幸福感的峰值

329
00:18:20,760 --> 00:18:24,410
So the key you want to maintain the spike is to do it regularly.
保持这个峰值的关键就是经常去做

330
00:18:24,630 --> 00:18:28,970
Either once a week. Once a week,two weeks. Once a month. Do it.
每周做一次 两周做一次或一月做一次

331
00:18:29,190 --> 00:18:32,960
You can do it one week a gratitude phone call and make it ritual.
一周打一次感激电话 把它变成仪式

332
00:18:33,360 --> 00:18:35,630
The next week,a gratitude letter.
下一周写信表达感激

333
00:18:35,830 --> 00:18:39,550
The week after that,a gratitude visit. Or something like that.
再下一周 感激拜访 以此类推

334
00:18:39,790 --> 00:18:42,410
Again,variety. Variety really helps here.
还是要有变化 形式的变化很有帮助

335
00:18:42,710 --> 00:18:44,210
But do it regularly as a ritual.
但把它作为一种仪式经常去做

336
00:18:44,420 --> 00:18:46,000
And when we talk about change next week,
下周谈"改变"时

337
00:18:46,290 --> 00:18:48,680
we'll talk about the importance of rituals.
我们会谈到"仪式"的重要性

338
00:18:49,360 --> 00:18:49,800
Because in many ways,
因为在很多方面

339
00:18:50,010 --> 00:18:53,470
that's the only change for real,lasting change.
那是唯一的真正持久的改变

340
00:18:56,600 --> 00:18:58,250
Here's one of the surprising findings
有一项惊人的发现

341
00:18:58,430 --> 00:19:00,220
that Sonja Lyubomirsky found.
是Sonja Lyubomirsky的发现

342
00:19:00,520 --> 00:19:02,590
What she found is that if we write that letter,
她发现如果我们写了那封信

343
00:19:02,940 --> 00:19:06,220
we get the spike in wellbeing even if we don't send it.
就算不寄出去 幸福感也能达到的峰值

344
00:19:06,520 --> 00:19:08,940
Obviously if we send it and we get feedback,
寄出去当然会得到回应

345
00:19:09,200 --> 00:19:10,600
the spike is even higher.
峰值会更高

346
00:19:10,810 --> 00:19:14,650
But just the act of writting it,of being grateful,being open,
但仅仅是书写 感受感激之情 敞开心扉

347
00:19:16,890 --> 00:19:20,330
that in and of itself contributes to wellbeing. Next week,
这样做的本身也有助提升幸福感 下周

348
00:19:20,580 --> 00:19:23,610
your response paper is going to be a letter of gratitude,
你们的功课就是一封感激信

349
00:19:23,840 --> 00:19:26,190
which we will highly recommend you visit the person
我们强烈建议你们去拜访对方

350
00:19:26,430 --> 00:19:28,050
and read it to them or,at the very least,
把信读给他们 或者最起码

351
00:19:28,220 --> 00:19:31,970
send it if you are not close to them now physically.
把信寄出去 如果你们相隔很远

352
00:19:33,370 --> 00:19:34,440
But even if you just write it
但即使是写了信

353
00:19:34,710 --> 00:19:36,250
and don't feel comfortable sending it,
却不好意思寄出去

354
00:19:36,470 --> 00:19:39,890
that in and of itself contributes to our wellbeing.
那同样能提升你的幸福感

355
00:19:42,060 --> 00:19:44,550
I want to go a little bit more in depth into
我想再深入谈谈

356
00:19:44,790 --> 00:19:47,270
how we express gratitude and in general,
如何表达感激 再概况谈谈

357
00:19:47,480 --> 00:19:51,750
how we deal with painful and positive emotions.
如何应对痛苦和积极的情绪

358
00:19:52,040 --> 00:19:54,520
Once again,Sonja Lyubomirsky did research,
再次引用Sonja Lyubomirsky所做的研究

359
00:19:54,750 --> 00:19:57,830
while she invited participants to talk about
她邀请参与者谈论

360
00:19:58,100 --> 00:20:01,380
or to share the worst experiences of their lives
分享生活中最糟的经历

361
00:20:01,710 --> 00:20:04,440
and the best experiences of their lives.
和最好的经历

362
00:20:04,790 --> 00:20:08,120
And what she did was divide them actually to four groups.
她所做的是把他们分成四组

363
00:20:08,370 --> 00:20:10,250
One group- write about it.
第一组 写出来

364
00:20:10,480 --> 00:20:15,000
Write about the ABC,the affect- the emotion,the behavior-
写出三方面 一是影响 也就是情感 二是行为

365
00:20:15,410 --> 00:20:18,790
what you did then,and the cognition- what you thought then.
即当时你做了什么 三是认知 即当时的想法

366
00:20:20,440 --> 00:20:24,880
Three times on three consecutive days for 15 minutes.
连续三天 每天一次 每次15分钟

367
00:20:25,140 --> 00:20:26,810
First group just wrote about it.
第一组只是写出来

368
00:20:27,200 --> 00:20:30,960
The second group talked about it to a tape recorder
第二组对着录音机说

369
00:20:32,800 --> 00:20:35,150
about the same best experiences and another group,
讲述最好的经历 另一组

370
00:20:35,370 --> 00:20:36,270
worst experiences.
讲述最糟的经历

371
00:20:37,790 --> 00:20:39,640
Third group,just think about it-
第三组 只是去想

372
00:20:39,900 --> 00:20:43,600
ruminate for 15 minutes also on three consecutive days.
连续三天 每天沉思15分钟

373
00:20:45,170 --> 00:20:48,930
What she looked at was physical and mental health.
她观察他们身体和心理的健康状况

374
00:20:49,170 --> 00:20:51,210
She looked at how healthy they were.
她观察他们的健康程度

375
00:20:51,450 --> 00:20:52,570
She looked at their physical...
观察他们的身体

376
00:20:52,810 --> 00:20:54,900
how they perceived themselves as healthy or not,
他们认为自己有多健康

377
00:20:55,190 --> 00:20:56,850
how many symptoms they actually had.
他们有多少种病症

378
00:20:57,100 --> 00:21:00,550
And she looked at their mood- how happy they were.
她还观察他们的情绪 他们有多快乐

379
00:21:01,110 --> 00:21:03,830
Before the experiment and four weeks later,
观察期是实验前和实验后的四周

380
00:21:04,070 --> 00:21:07,680
after that three days,15 minutes each day intervention.
经过三天 每天15分钟的干预后

381
00:21:07,960 --> 00:21:10,550
There was also a fourth group,which was a control group.
还有第四组 是一个对照组

382
00:21:16,220 --> 00:21:17,610
Here is what she found.
她的发现如下

383
00:21:19,120 --> 00:21:24,750
So basically you have three or four by two,
一共有三或四组 每组作两项研究

384
00:21:25,260 --> 00:21:27,550
writting,talking and thinking.
书写 谈论和沉思

385
00:21:27,860 --> 00:21:32,390
Study one: worst experiences. Study two: best experiences.
研究一是最糟的经历 研究二是最好的经历

386
00:21:32,800 --> 00:21:35,630
Those who wrote- let me just explicate this.
书写的人 我来解释一下

387
00:21:35,870 --> 00:21:41,570
Those who wrote about the worst experiences actually felt better
书写最糟经历的人事实上感觉更好了

388
00:21:42,090 --> 00:21:43,220
and were physically healthier,
身体上也更健康

389
00:21:43,440 --> 00:21:46,870
compared to the control group four weeks later.
这是经过四周后与对照组相比的结果

390
00:21:47,610 --> 00:21:50,740
Those who talked about it to a take recorder- remember?
对着录音机说的那些人 还记得吗?

391
00:21:50,980 --> 00:21:52,960
about what they felt,about what they've been through,
谈论他们的感受 他们的经历

392
00:21:53,210 --> 00:21:56,730
about what they thought at the time while they are thinking now.
谈论当时的想法和现在的想法

393
00:21:57,020 --> 00:21:58,640
15 minutes,three days.
15分钟 连续三天

394
00:21:58,990 --> 00:22:02,400
Actually,felt better after talking about it.
在谈论之后感觉更好了

395
00:22:05,430 --> 00:22:07,420
Those who thought about it,
那些想的人

396
00:22:07,620 --> 00:22:10,480
who ruminated about it,without talking,
沉思的人 不去谈论

397
00:22:10,510 --> 00:22:13,000
without writting about it,actually felt worse
不去书写 他们感觉更糟了

398
00:22:13,210 --> 00:22:16,510
and were physically less healthier a month later.
一个月后身体状况也更糟

399
00:22:20,980 --> 00:22:22,480
The second study,
研究二

400
00:22:22,770 --> 00:22:24,820
where they wrote about their happiest experiences,
他们书写最快乐的经历

401
00:22:25,060 --> 00:22:28,190
we see the opposite trend. In other words,
我们看到相反的趋势 换言之

402
00:22:28,450 --> 00:22:31,190
those who wrote about it on what they experience,
那些连续三天书写他们的经历

403
00:22:31,410 --> 00:22:35,690
how they experience it,what they learn from it on three days,
如何经历以及汲取的教训的人

404
00:22:35,920 --> 00:22:37,310
for 15 minutes each time,
每次15分钟

405
00:22:37,600 --> 00:22:43,750
actually felt worse physically as well as mentally after a month.
一个月后身体和心理上都感觉更糟

406
00:22:44,250 --> 00:22:46,370
Those who talked about it also about the ABC-
那些谈论这三样的人

407
00:22:46,610 --> 00:22:48,530
the affect,the behavior,the cognition,
即影响 行为和认知

408
00:22:48,780 --> 00:22:53,370
also felt better and were less healthy a month later.
一个月后同样感觉更好但身体状况更差

409
00:22:53,910 --> 00:22:55,650
Well those who just thought about it,
而那些只是想的人

410
00:22:55,870 --> 00:22:57,960
ruminated about their positive experiences,
沉思他们的积极经历的人

411
00:22:58,220 --> 00:23:02,710
imagined it on three consecutive days,15 minutes each day,
连续三天 每天15分钟想像它的人

412
00:23:03,100 --> 00:23:07,040
actually felt better and were healthier a month later,
一个月后感觉更好更健康

413
00:23:07,330 --> 00:23:11,470
four weeks later. So she ran the third study to understand-
四周后的结果 于是她进行第三项研究去了解

414
00:23:11,690 --> 00:23:14,020
this was a surprising result,was not what she expected.
这是很惊人的结果 出乎她的预料

415
00:23:14,640 --> 00:23:17,010
So she ran the third study to understand the mechanism-
于是她进行第三项研究去了解其中的机制

416
00:23:17,220 --> 00:23:19,080
what is going on here. Why is it that
这是怎么回事 为什么

417
00:23:19,270 --> 00:23:23,180
when we write and talk about negative experiences,
当我们书写和谈论消极经历时

418
00:23:23,430 --> 00:23:25,210
it makes us feel better and healthier?
我们会感觉更好更健康?

419
00:23:25,550 --> 00:23:26,950
Strengthen our immune system?
增强我们的免疫系体?

420
00:23:27,590 --> 00:23:30,360
Whereas when we just think about it,ruminate it,
但当我们思考或沉思时

421
00:23:30,590 --> 00:23:31,870
what's going on here?
发生什么事?

422
00:23:32,170 --> 00:23:36,900
Whereas the exact opposite is the case with positive emotions.
思考积极情感时却产生相反的结果

423
00:23:37,150 --> 00:23:39,590
And what she found was there was a distinction
她的发现是

424
00:23:39,790 --> 00:23:41,800
between analyzing and replaying.
分析和重现之间是有区别的

425
00:23:42,640 --> 00:23:44,890
When we analyze an experience,
当我们分析一次经历时

426
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:49,480
when we make sense of it,it helps. It actually helps.
当我们理清它时 它真得有帮助

427
00:23:49,800 --> 00:23:51,460
Painful experiences and negative experiences,
痛苦的经历和消极的经历

428
00:23:51,670 --> 00:23:54,200
which is why therapy helps. And
所以心理治疗才有帮助

429
00:23:54,430 --> 00:23:57,400
what helps in therapy more than anything is less of technique,
心理治疗中最有帮助的 除了技术

430
00:23:57,990 --> 00:24:02,360
less the years of study that the therapists had,
除了心理治疗师的多年学习

431
00:24:02,640 --> 00:24:05,610
less the experience that the therapists had. These things matter.
除了心理治疗师的经验 这些都很重要

432
00:24:05,910 --> 00:24:09,290
But not that much. What matters most is are they empathic.
但不是最重要的 最重要的是他们的感同身受

433
00:24:09,570 --> 00:24:11,930
In other words,are they good listeners? so
换言之 他们是不是好的聆听者?

434
00:24:12,180 --> 00:24:15,730
when we feel like we can talk and analyze about painful emotion,
当我们觉得可以谈论或者分析痛苦情绪时

435
00:24:15,950 --> 00:24:18,630
we feel better. We are physically healthier.
我们感觉更好 身体更健康

436
00:24:18,970 --> 00:24:20,240
When we simply sit down
当我们只是坐下来

437
00:24:20,470 --> 00:24:25,260
and ruminate about painful emotions without making sense of it,
沉思痛苦的情绪却不去理清它时

438
00:24:25,500 --> 00:24:27,890
we get very often into a downward spiral.
我们经常进入下行螺旋

439
00:24:28,980 --> 00:24:31,800
We narrow and constrict. We feel more sad.
我们收窄压缩 感觉更悲哀

440
00:24:32,100 --> 00:24:34,020
We narrow and constrict even more.
进一步收窄压缩

441
00:24:34,260 --> 00:24:36,120
Remember the Barbara Fredrickson's studies?
还记得Barbara Fredrickson的研究吗？

442
00:24:36,430 --> 00:24:41,600
And so on and so on. In contrast,we are not sure why.
不断恶化 相反 虽然不清楚原因

443
00:24:41,890 --> 00:24:45,140
when we analyze a positive experience,really analyze it-
当我们分析积极的经历时 真正地分析它

444
00:24:45,400 --> 00:24:47,270
try to understand why it happened and so on.
尝试理解为什么会发生等等

445
00:24:47,450 --> 00:24:49,720
So we do it for three consecutive days.
连续这样做三天

446
00:24:51,060 --> 00:24:56,030
It actually dosen't help. We don't understand why.
它确实没有帮助 我们不明白为什么

447
00:24:56,300 --> 00:24:58,640
But maybe it's because it takes all the fun spontaneity
也许是因为让我们回忆起

448
00:24:58,840 --> 00:25:00,480
from the experience.
经历的快乐之处

449
00:25:00,950 --> 00:25:04,610
However when we just ruminate about the positive experience-
但当我们只是沉思积极经历时

450
00:25:04,820 --> 00:25:08,120
just think about it,then it contributes to our well-being.
只是想也会提升我们的幸福感

451
00:25:08,350 --> 00:25:12,470
The gratitude exercise is about replaying the experience.
感激修习就是重播快乐经历

452
00:25:12,920 --> 00:25:15,500
It's exactly that. In other words,
就是如此 换言之

453
00:25:15,750 --> 00:25:19,740
it's thinking about our happiest experiences of the day,
就是说回想最快乐的日子

454
00:25:20,150 --> 00:25:22,740
which leads ultimately to positive outcome.
能自动导致积极的结果

455
00:25:23,580 --> 00:25:26,180
So what is it saying aobut the permission to be human?
那么准许为人说的是什么?

456
00:25:27,310 --> 00:25:28,700
How is it different?
有什么区别?

457
00:25:28,940 --> 00:25:32,110
Because the permission to be human is also very much related
因为准许为人也是为了

458
00:25:32,320 --> 00:25:34,520
to being happier and healthier in the long term.
实现长期的快乐和健康

459
00:25:34,750 --> 00:25:36,920
Well here's the difference: with the permission to be human,
区别是这样的 准许为人

460
00:25:37,110 --> 00:25:40,210
we give ourselves the permission to experience the emotions
我们准许自己感受各种情绪

461
00:25:41,580 --> 00:25:42,980
for as long as necessary.
只要有必要

462
00:25:43,210 --> 00:25:44,960
If we just lost someone,it would be much longer
失去亲人时 我们准许自己感受情绪的时间

463
00:25:45,190 --> 00:25:48,590
than if we just didn't perform so well in the test. But
远比考试失利的时间要长

464
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:52,050
we give ourselves the permission to experience the experience.
但我们准许自己感受经历

465
00:25:52,280 --> 00:25:53,520
And then we ask ourselves,
然后我们自问

466
00:25:54,280 --> 00:25:57,450
"so what would be the most effective way to act now?"
"现在最有效的行动是什么?"

467
00:25:57,690 --> 00:25:59,230
And one fo the most effective way to act
最有效的行动之一

468
00:25:59,440 --> 00:26:01,720
would be to share that experience.
是去分享那次经历

469
00:26:01,950 --> 00:26:03,220
One fo the most effective way to act
最有效的行动之一

470
00:26:03,430 --> 00:26:08,090
would be to just write in our journal. Daily active acceptance.
是写日记 接受每天的行为

471
00:26:08,370 --> 00:26:12,460
Not just ruminating and staying there with this painful emotion.
不要苦苦沉思痛苦的情绪

472
00:26:12,760 --> 00:26:14,070
Now one of the things I thought about it
我思考的一件事

473
00:26:14,250 --> 00:26:18,120
also in the context of my grandmother's experience
也与祖母的经历有关

474
00:26:18,380 --> 00:26:23,320
is why is it that- we'll talk about PTSD in a few minutes-
为什么会那样 一会我们会谈到PTSD

475
00:26:23,530 --> 00:26:24,160
why is it that
为什么会那样

476
00:26:24,350 --> 00:26:27,600
so many people in the United States coming back from Vietnam
从越南回国的很多美国人

477
00:26:27,850 --> 00:26:33,050
30% of Vietnam vets experience post traumatic stress disorder.
30%的越战老兵都患有严重创伤后遗症

478
00:26:33,890 --> 00:26:36,220
It affected their entire lives.
那影响了他们整个人生

479
00:26:37,310 --> 00:26:40,010
Whereas people who have been through the holocaust,
但经历过大屠杀的人

480
00:26:40,320 --> 00:26:46,410
no less terrible experiences,very often,much worse experiences,
同样是可怕的经历 经常是更可怕的经历

481
00:26:47,290 --> 00:26:51,620
people who have been through the holocaust,percentage wise-
经历过大屠杀的人 就百分比来说

482
00:26:51,850 --> 00:26:54,610
there are far less people who have PTSD-
患有PTSD的要少得多

483
00:26:54,850 --> 00:26:58,040
post traumatic stress disorder. Why this difference?
严重创伤后遗症 为什么会有这种区别?

484
00:26:58,270 --> 00:27:02,300
I mean,you know in Israel,50% of the older population-
我知道在以色列 50%的老年人

485
00:27:02,480 --> 00:27:06,390
when I was born,50% of the population were holocaust survivers.
在我出生时 50%的人口都是大屠杀幸存者

486
00:27:06,620 --> 00:27:09,130
I didn't see much post traumatic stress disorder there.
我没看到有很多严重创伤后遗症患者

487
00:27:09,370 --> 00:27:13,610
Whereas again,30% of Vietnam vets have PTSD.
但30%的越战老兵都有PTSD

488
00:27:13,840 --> 00:27:14,860
Now the jury is still out to see
现在陪审团正在调查

489
00:27:15,060 --> 00:27:18,370
how many of the second Iraq war will come back with PTSD,
二次伊战老兵有多少患PTSD

490
00:27:18,580 --> 00:27:20,500
but the number is going to be staggering too.
数字一定也很惊人

491
00:27:21,530 --> 00:27:22,650
Why? What's the difference?
为什么? 为什么有这样的区别?

492
00:27:22,890 --> 00:27:24,890
And I think this explains the difference.
我认为这就是解释

493
